One thing to keep in mind with regard to natural language is that natural language is often highly imprecise, and very dependant upon the level of eloquence of the transmitter and the knowledge and understanding of the receiver, and the importance of shared points of reference for both of them.

This is why for instance when it comes to the sciences there is such a heavy emphasis on exact word use. When writing a scientific article or instruction manual, you want to be as precise as possible with your use of words, terms and grammer and to minimize the chance of missunderanding to be as small as possible. 

That is why, even if computers could understand natural language, the degrees of complexity of the tasks which they could pull off would inevitably be affected by the accuracy of the instructions(macros and preprogrammed sequences and programs are of course exempted).

In the video where u talk about black holes u said that time would speed up for someone falling in to a black holes but would that mean u could see the black hole that u are falling in to died like black hole supernova and if i was at the a black hole and i was one meter away from the evethorisen could i see the future and get back to Earth i would be dead but could i??

Wrong course. You'd be better off asking this on SpaceTime. 

To attempt to answer your question: as far as we know "information" is never destroyed. This is a consequence of a law of the universe that matter can never be destroyed. So all the matter, including energy and light, that goes into a blackhole just stays there. So if you were to enter a blackhole (without dieing) you would have access to all of that information meaning you could see the past; like a cosmic archive or history book.

But, because of the crazy amount of gravity that's happening to cause this affect, time would speed up for you almost infinitely due to the extreme spacetime warp while at the same time someone watching you from outside the blackhole it would look like time had infinitely slowed down for you. 

You would quickly see the death of the blackhole due to evaporation, but because you're seeing all the information being released, from your perspective it would look like you're traveling back in time back towards the creation of the blackhole. What you would see after that point is a complete mystery. Science has never observed the complete evaporation of a blackhole.

Little correction: Phonems are from the realm of Phonology, not Phonetics. The corresponding unit from Phonetics is a Phon. The distinction is important, because Phons are a physics based unit while Phonems are a mind based unit. One Phonem can contain many multiple Phons, which are then referred to as Allophones.

Okay, so I'll admit I've never actually read that book, but... wasn't that about burning books? What does that have to do with NLP?

Fahrenheit 451 Is not a book about a world where firemen don't put out fires, but burn books. 

It is a book about the path the world took to become a world where firemen don't put out fires, but instead burn books.

(Spoiler alert:They burned the books to appease not the great powers that be, but the whining perpetually offended people who just wouldn't shut up, and now everyone lives in a socialist hell.)

Basically TV & electronic entertainment have taken over as books have been made illegal. These technologies are highly addictive as you might imagine. The main character's wife wears these wireless headphone type devices that she never takes out & are always on, even in her sleep. It's part of an endless stream of media that designed to keep the citizens in this dystopia from thinking too deeply. 
See I bring this up because when Carrie's talking about speech synthesis & how more of our devices are becoming more interactive in regards to speech, it eerily reminded me of this. I will admit it scared me.

Fahrenheit 451 isn't about banning / burning books or machines taking over. It's about a society having been constantly on the brink of being destroyed in a nuclear war for so long that everyone is driven to short term distractions (TV, drugs, fast cars, etc) in order to drown out the fear. The populace collectively decides to burn books because they want to forget about the past.

Do any modern speech synthesizers just generate artificial sound with an acoustic model of the human mouth and vocal tract? With how fast ray tracing for graphics has become, certainly we must have soundwave-tracing for audio by now?

While that's an interesting idea, I don't think it would really help much at all. In the end, you'd still be stringing together phonemes; you'd just represent them as vocal geometries rather than sound waves, and then produce the sound waves from them. So you'd probably get similar results, but it'd be much less efficient to calculate.

There are 2 main methods for speech synthesis, the one is taking bits of audio, cutting it up and playing it back (unit selection) the other is to find some statistics on speech, model them and use a generative model to produce novel speech. I work for a speech synthesis company called Cereproc and we do both. The unit selection sounds much better, but the parametric requires less data, on our site you can hear samples of both.

When doing parametric synthesis one method that is used is called source filter separation. Here you split the signal into 2 parts and while they don't exactly match the vocal track and articulators it is a similar idea.

One of the simpler ways to make a "dumb" chatbot is to give it a small set of default "conversation starters" to randomly choose from. Whenever a user says something it doesn't know about, it responds "I didn't understand that", but adds what the user said to its conversation starters. Whenever it chooses a conversation starter, it logs what the user responds as an "appropriate response" and now it knows how to respond to one more possible input :)

Of course, even for a "dumb bot", you may still want to do some input normalization to get a more generic set of matched inputs for responses, but that's up to you :)

why don't you write the code like this?:

import nltk
from nltk import pos_tag, PunktSentenceTokenizer
from nltk.corpus import state_union

def process_content(tokenized):
    for i in tokenized:
        words = nltk.word_tokenize(i)
        tagged = pos_tag(words)
        print(tagged)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    train_text = state_union.raw("2005-GWBush.txt")
    sample_text = state_union.raw("2006-GWBush.txt")
    custom_sent_tokenizer = PunktSentenceTokenizer(train_text)
    tokenized = custom_sent_tokenizer.tokenize(sample_text)
    process_content(tokenized)

A corpus is a large body of natural language text used for accumulating statistics on natural language text. The plural is corpora. Corpora often include extra information such as a tag for each word indicating its part-of-speech, and perhaps the parse tree for each sentence. Hope that solves your query.

How does Keras know to return the same integer value for a word in the training text as in the text you are going to load and do a prediction on. If Keras does not return "42" for the same word in the training text and "42" for the same word in the prediction text, won't the sentiment be incorrect? Does this make sense what I am asking?

I'm not sure that I understand your question, but the Tokenizer will map words in any text to integers. We "train" the Tokenizer on the training-data so its vocabulary is a subset of the most frequent words in the training-data. If your new text has a new word, then the Tokenizer won't know how to map it to an integer and it'll just be skipped.

So if you have 100 words of text and the word "water" is given the integer value of 10 by the tokenizer. If you then send another 500 words of text to the tokenizer, and "water" appears in the "that" text as well but in different places in the new text, will the tokenizer still give the word "water" the integer value of 10 ??? If not then am I understanding this correctly is with this process, you can't introduce new "text" into the system since the tokenizer indexing will be totally different ??

Yes, you build a vocabulary inside the tokenizer. The data-set may have a vocabulary of 100k words but we may only use the 10k most frequent words. If you see a word outside of this 10k vocab, the tokenizer will ignore it when converting texts to integer-sequences. Furthermore, the Embedding-layer will expect that the words map to the same integers, so you can't change the vocab and tokenizer without also retraining the Embedding-layer.
These are Python Notebooks so the best thing is to play around with the code to try and figure out the exact semantics. Often the official docs may be unclear on something and the only way to find out is to add print-statements and see exactly what is going on.

I had the exact same question, thanks for asking and clarifying. For those wondering, here is the answer to this. Keras has 2 methods (just like Sklearn fit and transform). Tokenizer.fit_on_texts() works like fit function and updates/creates the vocabulary + indexes, while Tokenizer.texts_to_sequences() behaves as transform and uses the existing vocab to simply convert text to sequences. If a new word is introduced, it skips its index since that would not be a part of the vocab.

Really appreciate the videos, but I think this should really be mentioned here as well. As others mentioned in the last video, the instability is because you take the top 3000 of the dictionary, which are different every time. You should call all_word.most_common(3000) to get the top 3000 most common ones, now you get a random selection.

Actually, your solution doesn't entirely work by itself. If you really want the 3000 most common words, and not a random grab, read this (however, there is a major flaw to this):

all_words.keys()[:3000] is pulling the top 3000 words, but it's pulling from a dictionary, which are not ordered in python. This means you're not grabbing the top 3000 most used words, but the top 3000 unordered words in your dictionary. Unfortunately, you cant just change all_words.keys()[:3000] to all_words.most_common(3000) because this just simply coverts it to a list of tuples, meaning it grabs the entire tuple consisting of the word and the count, which won't correctly classify words for positivity or negativity later (try it to see why).

Instead, to fix this, the first thing to do is use the all_words.most_common(3000) to covert it to a list. Then, use a for loop to iterate through the list of tuples. However, keep in mind, the tuples are like small dictionaries themselves so as you iterate through the list you made(all_words) you have to make sure you're specifying the key and value of each tuple so that you can grab just the word (which is stored as the key in the tuple. The count of frequency-use is the value). My code below is tested and works.

Posted just below the line all_words = nltk.FreqDist(all_words)
word_features = []
all_words = all_words.most_common(3000) #This makes a list of tuples of the 3000 most commonly used words, to include words like 'the' and 'by' or punctuation, so it's correct, but not entirely useful.
for key,value in all_words: #We are iterating through tuples in our list, each of which has a key and a value.
    word_features.append(key)    #This grabs only the word.

Cons to this however: If you choose to do this, it doesn't disclude useless words. Words like 'the' is going to always appear more frequently, so using it as part of your classifier is actually giving you a more unreliable result. This method is really only more efficient if you are first using a stop words or chunking algorithm to remove words that aren't going to be reliable for measuring your positivity or negativity. is it possible to get an accuracy of 90%+ while using pickle. I tried it thrice and it gave me 99, 92 and 95% accuracy which is insane.

The pickle file here does not affect on your accuracy. It's just for performance. You can pickle several models and try to train and test them, and you will see the difference (if you understand what NB is about)

In this tutorial, the same corpus was used both for training and testing datasets. So if you split your entire dataset like 75% for training, and test it with the rest 25% of the same corpus, then you will probably get some high accuracy with the low bias as NB is the simple, however you need to take care of the balance so called "bias-variance tradeoff" where you shouldn't tune your Naive Bayes model with the specific datasets, otherwise your model's variance will be increasing.

@violinov Good question. I used to just split them using traditional string splitting, but you can actually do it correctly. Chunked is an nltk tree, with subtrees. So, we can reference all of these subtrees by doing chunked.subtrees. Then we want to filter these for specific labels. In our case, we're calling our label "Chunk" (see the regular expression we write).

So, we can do something like:
            for subtree in chunked.subtrees(filter=lambda t: t.label() == 'Chunk'):
                print(subtree)


Full code would look something like:

import nltk
from nltk.corpus import state_union
from nltk.tokenize import PunktSentenceTokenizer

train_text = state_union.raw("2005-GWBush.txt")
sample_text = state_union.raw("2006-GWBush.txt")

custom_sent_tokenizer = PunktSentenceTokenizer(train_text)

tokenized = custom_sent_tokenizer.tokenize(sample_text)

def process_content():
    try:
        for i in tokenized:
            words = nltk.word_tokenize(i)
            tagged = nltk.pos_tag(words)
            chunkGram = r"""Chunk: {<RB.?>*<VB.?>*<NNP>+<NN>?}"""
            chunkParser = nltk.RegexpParser(chunkGram)
            chunked = chunkParser.parse(tagged)
            
            print(chunked)
            for subtree in chunked.subtrees(filter=lambda t: t.label() == 'Chunk'):
                print(subtree)

            chunked.draw()

    except Exception as e:
        print(str(e))

process_content()

I am a little bit confused. From Wikipedia, 1st order Markov assumption only considers the previous one word. But from your definition, 1st Markov assumption means words are independent to each other.

Hmm, good question... well this page mentions that the n^th order corresponds to conditioning on the n-1 previous words, as in my slide: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Language_model#n-gram_models . That's the definition I'm familiar with.

Looks like the nth order Markov property does consider, for w_t, w_t-n, as YuMao noted. However, the n-gram model does consider each word independent of every word for n = 1, i.e. the bag of words model. Which is to say that an n-gram model has the Markov property of degree n-1. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bag-of-words_model#N-gram_model

t and n are different things here. 

t indexes the words over the sentence when we're iterating to get the conditional probabilities of each word (so it goes from 1 to T, where T is the length of the sentence)

n is the order of the language model, so it is fixed to some value (e.g. n=3 for a trigram).

Hope this helps!
